animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Master Beckley (or 'Beck' as he is fondly called by his foster family) is a 4-yr old small Wire Terrier mix, possibly some Jack Russell.
Beck is a sort of 'special needs' boy, as he was born with luxating patellas on both of his hind legs. What this means is that he walks like a 'crab' on his hind legs - so, he definitely has a "unique" gait. But, this does not slow him down at all. He runs and plays and does just fine. As he gets older, he will likely develop arthritis in his rear legs sooner than a dog without this condition.
This being said, Beck is a very sweet, happy and lovable boy. He particularly loves women. With men, it can take him some time to warm up to them, but it really depends. In his original foster home, he was fine with his foster dad (who is 69), but Beck seems to have a trust problem with younger males.
As noted, Beckley adores women, and, as you can see in some of his pictures, he loves his sweaters. He actually prefers to wear outfits as not!!! He sleeps with his foster Grandmother and gets along well with the other dogs in the house (a Cattle Dog and a very large English Bulldog/Am. Staff Terrier).
Beck is about 90% house trained, as the cold weather/snow is hard on him to go outside. However, his foster Mom does make sure he goes out on a regular basis.
Beck is a wonderful little man who needs a person who is willing to dote on him and love him for who the sweet, affectionate little guy that he is. We believe he would do best in a household with women only, or an older couple. Please consider making this sweet boy become a cherished member of your home.
If you have the time, willingness and ability to provide a loving, nurturing home to Beckley for his whole life, we'd love to hear from you. To pursue Beckley's adoption, you will need to register on www.safeatlast.net. (Click Register on the left-hand side of our homepage.) When you receive your password, please log back on to our website to complete the Safe at Last online adoption application. (Click Forms/Applications on the left-hand side of our home page.) Once we have your application, if we feel your home is a good match for Beckley, we will contact you by email to schedule the phone interview to commence the review process. Our process is very straightforward but does involve the phone interview, reference checks and a home assessment. An adoption fee of $425 also applies.
Please be advised that you cannot meet Beckley until you have been approved to adopt. We cannot consider you until you have submitted the completed Safe at Last online adoption application. Delay in submitting your application will put you at a disadvantage to other potentially qualified applicants.
Finally, Beckley is being fostered in the Oneonta/Morris NY area. Approved adopters are required to go to the foster home to complete the adoption. Adopters are also required to adhere to all COVID-19 safety protocols (including mask) when at the foster home.
Thank you for your interest in this sweet boy!
NY Rescue Registry No. RR 087.

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Apollo! Here is a video from the day he was saved! More to come!

https://youtu.be/Vt9opoazgQU

Apollo is just a toddler at 13 months old (approx. DOB tbd), male, 75 lbs (but thinks he is 10lbs)., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. Apollo was saved on New Years Eve from a very neglectful and isolating situation in Vermont. He was kept tied up in one room of a house after being abandoned by his owner in an apartment. He had sores on his legs we can only guess was a result of boredom. Apollo has missed out on so much since a puppy and a young dog! He is learning and is in process of catching up with our Trainer. Apollo is a big boy with a big bark but is a teddy bear at heart! His best home would be Intermediate Experience, active, no cats (loves to play and chase), would be strong (he is a strong boy) and he would be the only pet. Stay tuned for more information as Apollo is a new rescue!

If you are interested in fostering or adopting Apollo please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Buddy!

I am a big, oversized puppy and I love, love, love every person I’ve ever met. I’m a pretty big boy (70 pounds and growing) and I’m still learning how to control my floppy puppy body. I fall over and run into things a lot, but my foster mom and dad think it’s really cute and funny! Even though I’m a big boy, I think I’m the perfect size lap dog and love to lay on you, sit on you and snuggle and give you kisses non-stop.

My foster mom says I’m really smart. I didn’t have many rules before I came to her house, but I’ve already learned sit, paw and down. I also sit and wait to eat my meals every day because I’m a very polite boy!

I’m a PRO at potty training. I learned REALLY fast!!! I was a super nervous about my crate when I first came to live with my foster mom, but it’s just because I prefer to be right next to humans instead! I’m getting better with my crate every day and now sleep in my crate all through the night without crying.

I live with two dogs in my foster home and I LOVE them, but I’m still learning some manners, so you may need to be patient with me. I’m perfectly fine being your only Buddy, but if I have a dog sibling, they need to be tolerant and willing to help me learn how to play without getting too excited.

Thanks for reading about me, I can’t wait to meet you and see if I can be your best “Buddy” for life!

You must be over 21 and a home owner to adopt me. Please visit www.pittiesandpurrs.org to fill out an application. For further information contact adoptpitties@gmail.com

animal.description:
All people inquiring about pets listed as Courtesy Listings on the EAPL website and/or EAPL posting adoption boards should contact the current pet owner/rescue/shelter for answers to any questions and for final approval and placement. Please DO NOT CONTACT EAPL about courtesy listings. The pet owner/rescue/shelter and new owner shall make all arrangements on transferring the pet, information on history, vaccines, etc.

Name: Buddy (also answers to Butters) Age: ~10 Weight: 90 pounds

Color: Brown with a few white spots Gets along with: All adults and older children (10+)

Contact: 720-985-7018 or AdoptSweetBuddy@gmail.com

Buddy couldn't be a sweeter dog! He's older but has a lot of life left in him. He loves going on walks, running like a goof around the yard, and naps! The perfect home for Buddy is where he can nap, relax, and get pets. He needs to be the only pet in the home and any children need to be over 10. He is very friendly with everyone he meets but doesn't like kids climbing on him so he would be best in a home with older or no children. He loves sleeping in the sun and will follow it around the house throughout the day or lay outside in it when it's warm out. He LOVES a nice comfy dog bed but is just as happy to lay on blankets or a pile of laundry. Buddy is crate trained and can hang in his crate when you're away during the day or be left out, he'll just take naps the whole time. He likes stuffed toys and soft rubber ones, he is missing some teeth so he doesn't chew through them very quickly. He also loves all treats and will gladly eat medicine if you put it in some American cheese. He will follow you around the house because he loves being near people. Buddy is scared of fireworks and loud noises, creating a place for him to hide when that's happening really helps him. It's best if he gets to go outside to potty before fireworks start. He is also scared of any size vacuum and will run away from them. He is food motivated and has puppy dog eyes down! He'll eat any kind of treat and will love you for it! He's a great dog and deserves a great home!
animal.name: Buddy Courtesy Listing

animal.description:
DOB: November 2012
Weight: 28 lbs
Disposition: Smart, Friendly, Low energy

Aldrin is the canine embodiment of beauty and brains. This handsome fella is not only quite the looker, but he already has his basic commands down pat! We originally rescued Aldrin and his astronaut friends from San Bernardino in September 2013. He was adopted shortly after, but returned to us many years later. Aldrin is great with other dogs, and is currently in a very large play group with other small/medium dogs ranging from 6-46 pounds. He is housebroken and knows sit and shake on command. Aldrin has a tendency to nip at hands if he feels uncomfortable in a situation, so for this reason, he is not suited for a home with small children. Aldrin is an intelligent, stately, calm, easygoing, and sweet boy who enjoys human attention. Don't be surprised if he leans up against you asking for more petting and belly rubs! 

Aldrin LOVES hanging out in the yard and while he needs to be an indoor pet, we will only entertain families with a yard for this reason. He will do best with an individual or couple of an assertive nature or with experience to correct any potential behavior related to nipping.

If you'd like to meet Aldrin, please visit www.thebarkinglot.net/adoptTo initiate the adoption process for this dog, please complete our online application by clicking below. Your adoption coordinator will respod to you via email once they receive your application: www.thebarkinglot.net/adopt

animal.description: I'm searching...Searching for a job. Ahhh, yes. A job would be very nice! During this pandemic, I've spent a lot of time sitting and doing nothing! I'm going crazy! I want a purpose! A job where I would be outside would be very nice! Picture this! You, me, doing something! I could carry your tools for you and happily assist you! Need to work on your truck? Cool, I have your back! Need to fix some fencing? Awesome, I'll help you! I love being outside and would LOVE to be in a home where we can hike, fish, camp, and explore. Being the only pet in the home would make me so incredibly happy. Actually, that's EXACTLY what I want. A home with me and you. I need to be the only baby in the home! I would thrive in a home with kids 14 and older.All cats and dogs adopted from the Chequamegon Humane Association are spayed or neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, and microchipped. Dogs are tested for heartworm and cats are tested for FeLV/FIV (results negative unless otherwise noted). A tax-deductible adoption fee of $150 is required for adult dogs, puppies are $200, and dogs over the age of 10 are $85. Adult cat adoption fees are $50, kittens under one year are $90, and cats over the age of 10 are $35.

animal.description:
Poor Bolt found himself at the City Shelter after he'd been picked up as a stray with a broken leg. Shelter staff loved him and his exuberant nature and did their best to give him the time to find rescue placement. We are so glad we could help. 

Despite the splint being changed, Bolts leg didn't heal due to the severe nature of the fracture. The vet recommended an amputation and the staff at Marley's agreed that Bolt's quality of life would improve with that treatment. No longer in pain, Bolt has recovered from the amputation and adjusted to the absence of that leg.

Bolt is looking for a wonderful forever home. His ideal home will be an active family looking for a fun and active pup to join their ranks. He's compatible with other canine friends. We feel he'd likely case kitties. 

Once healed Bolt will be looking for a wonderful forever home. His ideal home will be an active family looking for a fun and active pup to join their ranks. Once he's more healed we will dog test him to ensure he's compatible with other canine friends. We feel he'd likely case kitties. Stay tuned for updates as Bolt recovers. If you are interested in adopting a Marley's Mutts please fill out an application at http://marleysmutts.org/adoptionprocess/

animal.description:
Charlie Boy is estimated to be about 5 years old and almost fully blind. 
 

Sadly this sweet boy found himself homeless and was hanging out at a local shelter. He was terribly stressed out and was becoming super overwhelmed with fear. 
 

Happy Feet Pet Rescue welcomed him and placed him in a wonderful foster home. He was so overwhelmed with his stint in the shelter that he needed 24-48 hours to fully decompress and start to trust his new humans. He stayed in his crate for quite a bit before feeling courageous enough. 
 

After his decompression time he became the sweetest, loving, and oh so cuddly companion. He is fully potty trained, loves walks, and enjoys hanging out on the couch. 
 

Since Charlie lacks being able to see people approach, he relys on verbal commands or alerts. If he is surprised or gets nervous with a fast approach he may nip out of fear. 
 

We are recommending a home with no children, no other animals, and ideally a calm environment. 
 

If you can provide Charlie Boy a wonderful home please visit Happy Feet Pet Rescue website for an adoption application.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Greta and I'm a spunky little 10 week old hound puppy. I love to run and play and snuggle and sniff everything and everyone. I even met my new foster cat siblings and thought they were pretty neat!
I would love another dog in my foster home to show me the ropes and to play with. I am a true hound and as I grow will show my true natures- chasing, and baying. I will need a family who can help me channel my natural instincts and expose me to all the great parts of being a loved family member- with positive reward. 

Greta is a Hound puppy. Hounds are adorable and also high-energy. Hounds are typically bred for hunting and will likely have a very high prey drive, be vocal, and will need to have access to resources that will satisfy their energy level. Potential adopters should have a good understanding of the needs that come with having an active puppy and those of a working/hunting breed as well. Positive exposure and reinforcement are a must in her adoptive home, along with a solid plan for training and further socializing with other pets of all ages and sizes. 

To be considered, please start by applying online at caws.org. 
Greta's adoption fee is $300 and includes her fist year vaccines, spay and microchip. 

Please note that we carefully select each adoptive home to meet the needs of the animals in our care and not on a first come, first serve basis. Thanks! If you are interested in adopting a CAWS pet, please fill out an online application at https://caws.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Odie
Male
Age: 8 years old
Weight: 50 lbs
Breed: Akita/Shar Pei mix

How do you do? Im Odie! Although I may be a little bit older, my foster family says that is an added benefit for many reasons including how much love I have left to give! In my spare time, I enjoy taking my naps and lounging around; I consider myself a professional napper! I am housebroken and I am well behaved aside from the occasional trash diving. (It is recommended you have a lid on that when I am around! ) I also do well when given a bath; I just sit there without complaints! Also, Im a pretty quiet fella and do not bark much unless I need to use the restroom, I will be sure to let you know! I do well on a leash and take my walks for restroom breaks; I also enjoy getting doted on by passersby who always compliment me on my fuzzy coat and my cute ears!

Something I really enjoy the most is getting all the attention from my humans with pets and snuggles! I also love getting brushed; it feels so good! Pretty much anything that involves me getting attention will give you all the gold stars in my book! I am good with confident and friendly dogs and cats. I also enjoy going on trails and camping is a newly added item to my repertoire that I truly enjoy!

If you are interested in meeting the adorable Odie, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee:$195
Children must be 5 years old or older
Must be an Ohio resident 25 years old or older

animal.description:
Bonnie Blue
Female
Age: 3 years old
Weight: 50 lbs
Breed: Lab/Boxer mix

Hello there! Im Bonnie Blue, the sweetest snuggle girl around with piercing blue eyes that will melt your heart! I am a very loving girl with a playful demeanor who is eager to please my people! I am a bundle of energy and love who would do best in a home with an active family to keep me physically and mentally exercised. I walk very well on a leash and love hikes and long walks around the neighborhood. A fenced in yard would be best allowing me to get extra exercise in; however, it is not required so long as I have a committed family giving me the proper exercise to accommodate my energy. I absolutely love playing fetch and would play all day long if you would let me! I have been coexisting very well with my fur foster sister, but I will need slow introductions with new dogs since I am still working on building trust. I enjoy playing with my foster sister in the backyard, especially if mud is involved! I love to snuggle up on the couch with a blanket and my human. I am fully house trained and know basic obedience commands like sit, come, stay, but would love if someone would continue working with me on these skills! I am very food motivated and smart, so training should be super easy with me! I am working on my crate training and think it is going well; I am very motivated by treats!
I am the whole package, beautiful, smart, sweet, loyal, obedient and so very loving! All I want for my birthday is to find my forever home!

If you are interested in meeting the sweet, Bonnie Blue, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee $250.

Children must be 5 years old or older.
Must be an Ohio Resident at least 25 years old or older.

animal.description:
Mercy will be available starting Wednesday January 27th on our Adoptions Uncrated website at 7pm. https://www.followyourheartanimalrescue.org/shop

Mercy came to us from Mexico in early October barely alive. She has definitely rebounded! Mercy loves other dogs and FOOD. She loves peanut butter and treats! She also loves walks, but because of her limited vision, she becomes nervous and confused when there is a lot of commotion. She also pulls but has seen improvement with correction. We are working on desensitizing her to all that goes on in the neighborhood and heeling, but it's taking A LOT of time. She is mostly house trained. She knows sit, paw, and place. She uses a slow feeder bowl now, but she's almost to a place where she knows she'll have food each day and doesn't need to inhale it. I'm very excited with her progress and I'm so happy I could be a part of her physical and mental healing. ~ Foster mom, Debbie

animal.description: If you are into doggie hugs and you like small dogs then put this girl on your list! Camera is a little Spaniel and Chihuahua mix around 2 years old. She is super soft and has a nice caramel colored coat. This special girl is only about 20lbs but managed to deliver 6 big puppies who have all since been adopted. Camera takes time to warm up to new people then bonds closely to her humans but is not a big fan of visitors coming over to the house. She loves to sit on your lap and she will put her leg around your neck and then kiss you. She will jump up for attention and hugs as she is very affectionate. She is great on her nightly walks and will not go too far ahead of you. Typical to her breed, she gets a little scared if outside of her comfort zone. She can be a bit uncomfortable with new people in her life so allow her time to get to know them before forcing her to meet them. She would do best in a home without small children. Camera loves treats but they need to be good ones...like chicken or chicken! She is house trained and is learning to be in a crate. She is alert and will bark if someone comes to the door. Her foster mom just thinks she's a doll. If you are interested in meeting Camera, your first step would be to submit an adoption application on our website. If you are already approved with an adoption coach or have adopted from us before, reach out to your coach for the next steps. This information is as up to date and accurate as possible for the dog in its current environment. All dogs and puppies will need time and training to adjust to their new surroundings and to learn the rules of their new home. If you are interested in meeting one of our dogs, the first step is to complete the Adoption Form on our website at www.labsandmore.org and take some time to review our adoption process. Your adoption includes the spay or neuter, current vaccinations, microchip, and other services provided while in our care. The safety and health of our puppies is priority one, so we only allow approved applicants to meet and handle puppies. Please understand everything we do is for the dogs and conducted by our kind and generous volunteers. We rely solely on donations, and we do not profit from a dog's adoption. Labs and More is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that operates on donations and time dedicated to this cause by volunteers. Your adoption will save the life of future dogs in need. Labs and More makes no guarantees regarding the behavior, breed, or age of the dogs in our care. Although we strive to provide necessary medical care to dogs in our care, we cannot predict future or current medical needs whether they were symptomatic or not at the time of adoption.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Meet Gigi, a 34 pound, approximately 2 year old shepherd mix who is always excited to meet new people. This high energy girl is always ready for any adventure, whether a ride in the car, a hike in the woods, a walk around the block or a neighborhood jog, shes ready, willing and very able! Gigi is totally housebroken, does not appreciate the crate, prefers to sleep on your bed, does not like to be left alone, loves toys of all kinds, and would be happy to have at least 2 walks a day. She would be better with no children, as her mode of greeting is jumping, of which she is currently being worked with to break this habit. Proper training would be beneficial for her, as she has some habits which need to be changed and she is so smart that she would welcome the challenge. She would require a very secure yard as she is good at jumping over shorter barriers. A calm, assertive buddy would probably be a help to her, but another hyper dog may cause unwanted habits to appear. Gigi is a wonderful companion and has so much potential. She needs a family who will work with her to bring out more of her amazing self!

All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative (age 7 months and older) and microchipped. We do not ship or transport. A dog's adoption donation is $200. There is a $5 fee for credit/debit cards.

If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please fill out an online application here: www.heartlandsmallanimalrescue.org/canine-application.html

animal.description:
This adorable guy is Petey. He was found running at large and ended up at our shelter. We just can't imagine why he wasn't reclaimed -- he is the sweetest guy ever and has quickly melted our hearts.

Petey is a boxer-bulldog mix that we believe to be around 8 years old. He weights about 55 pounds. He is dog-friendly, kid-friendly, and just a big lover boy! He gives every indication of being housebroken.

With his age, he came with some health issues that we've addressed, and we continue to address some allergy problems he's having. Petey has experienced repeated ear infections that we recently learned is likely due to allergies. He is now on a special diet and time will tell if this is going to help. Petey is also hearing-impaired, although we don't know to what extent. 

In the meantime, we want to post Petey as a foster-to-adopt situation. We believe that Petey would do much better in a home environment where he can be monitored more closely, but we plan to keep him in foster status (where we cover his medical expenses) until his allergies are managed well.

Medical adventures aside, he's about the happiest guy we know! He's always smiling, loves getting loved on, and just wants to be part of a family. If you have a place in your heart and home for this sweet boy, please contact us.

---

animal.description:
Meet Paisley! She's about a year old and weighs 8 pounds. She was found wandering in the country, suspected to be dumped. No one claimed her during her 7-day hold at animal control, so she came to us at PCHS, and boy are we happy to have her!

As you can see, she's adorable! The shelter environment is stressful, especially for timid dogs, and so we're getting to know her slowly.

She is very timid right now and it doesn't seem she's ever been on a leash. However, she's a very sweet dog and will likely be like a little lapdog once she warms up. She really wants attention, but keeps a little bit of a distance initially, and when you pick her up her whole body gets stiff like she's nervous. But once she warms up, she jumps and plays, barks, and howls. She even gave one of volunteers a kiss on the nose the other day!

Once she's comfortable with you, she'll raise her little right paw and reach out she like she wants you to pet her, but then acts a little nervous when you do.

Because of her timid nature, she needs a home with no small children. An adult-only home would probably be best, although older kids who know to go slowly with her would likely be fine.

At an overnight with a volunteer, Paisley did well with the volunteer's dogs. (Of course, we always encourage a slow introduction between dogs.) Cats are an unknown right now.

We're not sure is Paisley is housebroken, but we think she'd be a quick learner once she's comfortable with her surroundings. She has also shown herself to a bit of a fence climber and escape artist (although it's hard to tell if that's just due to the stress of being at the shelter).

If you have the patience and love that Paisley needs, we think you'll be rewarded with a snuggly lapdog who wants nothing more than to be with you!

---

(PLEASE NOTE FRANNIE REQUIRES A FENCED IN YARD. SHE IS CURRENTLY ON THYROID MEDICATION AND BLOOD PRESSURE MEDICATION WHICH SHE MUST TAKE DAILY AS WELL AS A PRESCRIPTION DOG FOOD. HER NEW ADOPTER MUST BE WILLING TO CONTINUE WITH THIS REGIME.)

Hello, my name is Frannie, and I am a very lucky dachshund to have found Little Paws rescue when I did. My previous owner neglected my vet care and let me get so fat I couldn't breathe. I am now svelte (very sweet) 10 year old, and my health is as good as possible. I currently weigh 22 bs because I lost 10 whole lbs while in foster care.

I'm now a spokesdog for "The Green Bean Diet" Too bad it's not a paying gig ;)

What would make my heart soar

is a new fur-ever home with a fenced yard to sniff around in and bask in the sunshine.

I love being brushed, and I enjoy belly rubs.

I came into rescue with a bonded partner, Freckles, but I lost him to something called Cancer; whatever that is, it makes me sad. I'm hoping to find my person and heal my heart..could you be the one?

I am sociable with all people and other dogs.

If you have room in your home and heart for me and would like additional information about me, please contact my foster mom Lorrie at dachsielover@verizon.net

You can find the adoption application at: http://littlepawsdachshundrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form_humanverify?formid=2724

The adoption fee for me is $150. If I am adopted over a state line, there will be a $45.00 charge for a health certificate (required by law).

The Adoption Fee for Frannie is $150.00 + $45.00 for a health certificate if going over state lines (required by law). TRANSPORTATION HELP! animal.description:
Handsome old Klaus is looking for a new home. At age ~10 or 11, Klaus became homeless when his owner passed away. Some good Samaritans took him in as a favor to the man’s son, but are unable to keep him long term. 

We don’t have a ton of history on Klaus. Prior to the home he’s in now, he’d been living in an apartment with his owner, a man with a substance abuse problem and anger issues. When Klaus got to the home where he is now he acted like he’d never been on grass before. Thankfully he’s fully house trained, but would only potty on cement/hard surfaces outside (the driveway and walkways). He could barely walk, with an open sore on his leg that he had licked raw, and had horrible skin issues. On a good quality food, regular meals, bathing, fish oil and glucosamine supplements, his skin and coat look great now, and an Elizabethan collar keeps him from licking the leg, and the sore is healing well. He is a good boy for his baths and nail trims too. He gets around great now and moves nicely – no limping or soreness noted and he's spry and agile for his age.

Klaus is initially wary of people – he barks at new people entering the home – but within 5 minutes of me coming into the house he was fine with me. He allowed me to pet him all over and “talked” his way through all of it. This guy is a talker!  He enjoyed the pets and neck rubs, and was my new best friend in minutes. He made a beeline for my treat pocket and I ended up having to put my coat outside! He is learning the rules in his new home and doing very well with staying out of the kitchen and no begging when they eat. He’s very alert and responsive, food motivated, and loves any attention he gets.

While there’s no human aggression, Klaus does NOT like other dogs. A few weeks after he got to the home he got out of the fenced yard (gate not latched properly) and attacked a dog walking by the home. The dog had some bite wounds but was otherwise unharmed, and Klaus’s caretakers are now very careful to not let him out in the front yard. Long term they are concerned about this, and also have guests/family members who visit with their dogs, so keeping Klaus isn’t possible for them. 

We know that as a senior Rottweiler Klaus probably only has a couple years left, but this sweet old fellow deserves a place of his own, where he can be loved for the good dog he is, and enjoy his golden years in comfort. 

Go to https://spdrdogs.org/rescue-referral/how-to-adopt/ to fill out an adoption application for Klaus.

Washington State only - no interstate transports

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/SPDRRottweilerRescue

animal.description:
Meet Jordy!  Jordy is guessed to be about 2 years old and weighs approximately 9 lbs.  He was found as a stray and no one came to claim him, so he was transferred to us from a local shelter.  Jordy is a sweet boy who gets along with the other little dogs in his foster home and is doing well with potty training.  He is great at playing fetch and does well walking on a leash.  He loves running around the yard- even in the cold weather.   Jordy has experiences some food allergies in the past, although we haven't been able to identify exactly had causes him issues he is doing well with the food he is currently on.  Jordy has not gotten along with the 2 larger dogs in his foster home, so we think he would likely do best with dogs his size or smaller.  When he is afraid he will resort to barking and lunging- a form of fear aggression.  We are looking for a home that is willing to be patient with him, as well as work with him on building his confidence.  Jordy's adoption donation is $275 and helps cover his medical care. 

Application, reference checks, and home visit required. Adopters must live 1.5 hours driving distance from Romeoville, IL. For more information on adopting, please email us at info@perfectpooches.org.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application, which can be found on our website at www.perfectpooches.org under the Adoption Process tab.  All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on vaccines, heartworm tested (age appropriate), fecal tested and/or dewormed, and microchipped.

animal.description:
Hamlin is a 5 year old lab mix who weighs 70 pounds. He is one handsome fella and is looking for a family as active as he is! He loves running around in our play yard, making new friends, and living life to its fullest. If you like adventure and exploration, Hamlin might just be your guy!

He's a big, strong dog, but he knows to sit for treats and to go in/out of his run, and we think he would love to learn more.

Hamlin needs a forever home without cats or other male dogs. He also does well with his potty habits, leading us to believe he's either housebroken or could easily be.

---

Please know that if you come to meet any of the dogs at our facility, they may be excited to see you and extra active. Many times, this is not a true picture of how they may act in a warm, safe home setting. We, as volunteers, often take our shelter dogs on home visits and they become calm and act like completely different animals. This pertains to bathroom habits and demeanor. Please realize that they need a chance to shine out of the shelter setting!

Please call us at 618-542-DOGS(3647) or if you have any specific questions about me, please email the shelter volunteer at pchsinfo@yahoo.com or go to www.perrycountyhumanesocietyil.com to apply.

Sissy here! I am an 8 year old gal and boy could I tell you some stories... I was found in a vacant home after my people decided to leave me there alone with my 6 puppies -- I tried the best I could to take care of everyone but it was really hard. Thank goodness someone found us! These nice people are helping me find a real home with real people who will love me -- I can't wait!

I am a Boxer mix and I get along well with most other dogs, although I can be a bit picky and other girl dogs annoy me. I am housebroken, which I know is really important to most people. 

I weigh 61 pounds and I know I'm a little older than most dogs here, but I still have a lot of love to give and fun to experience. I'm a pretty energetic ol' gal! And I think it's my turn to be loved unconditionally like I have loved others my whole life.

(We don't know how Sissy is with kids yet, since we've not seen her around any yet.)

animal.description:
(PLEASE NOTE FRANNIE REQUIRES A FENCED IN YARD. SHE IS CURRENTLY ON THYROID MEDICATION AND BLOOD PRESSURE MEDICATION WHICH SHE MUST TAKE DAILY AS WELL AS A PRESCRIPTION DOG FOOD. HER NEW ADOPTER MUST BE WILLING TO CONTINUE WITH THIS REGIME.)

Hello, my name is Frannie, and I am a very lucky dachshund to have found Little Paws rescue when I did. My previous owner neglected my vet care and let me get so fat I couldn't breathe. I am now svelte (very sweet) 10 year old, and my health is as good as possible. I currently weigh 22 bs because I lost 10 whole lbs while in foster care.

I'm now a spokesdog for "The Green Bean Diet" Too bad it's not a paying gig ;)

What would make my heart soar

is a new fur-ever home with a fenced yard to sniff around in and bask in the sunshine.

I love being brushed, and I enjoy belly rubs.

I came into rescue with a bonded partner, Freckles, but I lost him to something called Cancer; whatever that is, it makes me sad. I'm hoping to find my person and heal my heart..could you be the one?

I am sociable with all people and other dogs.

If you have room in your home and heart for me and would like additional information about me, please contact my foster mom Lorrie at dachsielover@verizon.net

You can find the adoption application at: http://littlepawsdachshundrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form_humanverify?formid=2724

The adoption fee for me is $150. If I am adopted over a state line, there will be a $45.00 charge for a health certificate (required by law).

The Adoption Fee for Frannie is $150.00 + $45.00 for a health certificate if going over state lines (required by law). TRANSPORTATION HELP! If you see a furbaby that would be a match for your family, please don't let distance stand in the way of your adoption. LPDR can work with you to have a volunteer transport to assist with transportation or refer you to a paid transport.

animal.description:
Handsome old Klaus is looking for a new home. At age ~10 or 11, Klaus became homeless when his owner passed away. Some good Samaritans took him in as a favor to the man’s son, but are unable to keep him long term. 

We don’t have a ton of history on Klaus. Prior to the home he’s in now, he’d been living in an apartment with his owner, a man with a substance abuse problem and anger issues. When Klaus got to the home where he is now he acted like he’d never been on grass before. Thankfully he’s fully house trained, but would only potty on cement/hard surfaces outside (the driveway and walkways). He could barely walk, with an open sore on his leg that he had licked raw, and had horrible skin issues. On a good quality food, regular meals, bathing, fish oil and glucosamine supplements, his skin and coat look great now, and an Elizabethan collar keeps him from licking the leg, and the sore is healing well. He is a good boy for his baths and nail trims too. He gets around great now and moves nicely – no limping or soreness noted and he's spry and agile for his age.

Klaus is initially wary of people – he barks at new people entering the home – but within 5 minutes of me coming into the house he was fine with me. He allowed me to pet him all over and “talked” his way through all of it. This guy is a talker!  He enjoyed the pets and neck rubs, and was my new best friend in minutes. He made a beeline for my treat pocket and I ended up having to put my coat outside! He is learning the rules in his new home and doing very well with staying out of the kitchen and no begging when they eat. He’s very alert and responsive, food motivated, and loves any attention he gets.

While there’s no human aggression, Klaus does NOT like other dogs. A few weeks after he got to the home he got out of the fenced yard (gate not latched properly) and attacked a dog walking by the home. The dog had some bite wounds but was otherwise unharmed, and Klaus’s caretakers are now very careful to not let him out in the front yard. Long term they are concerned about this, and also have guests/family members who visit with their dogs, so keeping Klaus isn’t possible for them. 

We know that as a senior Rottweiler Klaus probably only has a couple years left, but this sweet old fellow deserves a place of his own, where he can be loved for the good dog he is, and enjoy his golden years in comfort. 

Go to https://spdrdogs.org/rescue-referral/how-to-adopt/ to fill out an adoption application for Klaus.

Washington State only - no interstate transports

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/SPDRRottweilerRescue

animal.description:
Meet Jordy!  Jordy is guessed to be about 2 years old and weighs approximately 9 lbs.  He was found as a stray and no one came to claim him, so he was transferred to us from a local shelter.  Jordy is a sweet boy who gets along with the other little dogs in his foster home and is doing well with potty training.  He is great at playing fetch and does well walking on a leash.  He loves running around the yard- even in the cold weather.   Jordy has experiences some food allergies in the past, although we haven't been able to identify exactly had causes him issues he is doing well with the food he is currently on.  Jordy has not gotten along with the 2 larger dogs in his foster home, so we think he would likely do best with dogs his size or smaller.  When he is afraid he will resort to barking and lunging- a form of fear aggression.  We are looking for a home that is willing to be patient with him, as well as work with him on building his confidence.  Jordy's adoption donation is $275 and helps cover his medical care. 

Application, reference checks, and home visit required. Adopters must live 1.5 hours driving distance from Romeoville, IL. For more information on adopting, please email us at info@perfectpooches.org.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application, which can be found on our website at www.perfectpooches.org under the Adoption Process tab.  All dogs are spayed/neutered, current on vaccines, heartworm tested (age appropriate), fecal tested and/or dewormed, and microchipped.

animal.description:
Katniss is a true winner of the Hunger Games.

Here she is having some fun with her buddy! https://youtu.be/kezLzIU6-MI


Found severely malnourished and near death in the back yard of a woman who contacted All 4's Rescue in Memphis, Tennessee - she had found her a week or so earlier but didn't realize how sick she was. Thank goodness she called for help. All 4's immediately contacted Paws New England and we could not resist this girl.

At 18 lbs in mid-November, she was truly near death - her optimal weight is 40-45 lbs and she's well on her way

Katniss is approximately one year old and is just gorgeous with her brindle coat. Her amazing foster family has nursed her back to health and she adores them and is loyal and seeks only to please and make them happy.

They are working on her resource guarding of food and treats meaning she is possessive of her food, treats etc. with the some of dogs in the home. Given her prior circumstances this is certainly understandable but she is getting better every day.With one dog she has no issues so honestly she is truly doing great in this regard.

She takes time to warm up to new people so a super busy home with kids/teenagers coming and going may not be ideal.

She is house trained, crate trained, walks on a leash, and knows how to sit and come. She loves her people; she's just not sure how to show it.

What would be great for her? Anyone that will be loving, attentive, and patient. Preferably with dog experience, she is not ideal for a first time dog owner.

Another dog in the home for her to play with would be amazing - she so enjoys their company - see video!!!


She gets along well with her female canine friend in the foster home and they play constantly. She does well on leash.

She is house trained and crate trained which is fabulous.


Name: Katniss
Breed: Plott Hound
Sex: Female
Age: 1 year (estimated)
Weight: 37 lbs
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Yes
Heartworm:Negative 
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Over 15 but a quiet home is most appropriate
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00



IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.


Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.


At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.

NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
***UPDATE***
Bubbly's foster mom says that he is coming along well. She said he's happy to see his people when they get home. He will walk up to his people for kisses and doesn't mind being pet on the paws, legs and chest. He's still a little leary about being pet on the head and back. He loves to play with other dogs and is starting to play with people as well. He also sleeps all night in his kennel. He still has a long way to go, but these changes happened in just one week! Imagine what a wonderful, little dog he could be in a few months!

This little sweetie was rescued from an overcrowded Texas shelter and brought to Wisconsin for a better life. Bubbly is a 4 month old puppy and weighs about 20 lbs. Bubbly is a very shy and untrusting of people. He has been at the Texas shelter since he was 2 months, so the only interaction he's had with people is the shelter staff coming in and out to clean and feed him. He will need a family that understands that he will need a lot of time and patience to learn to trust people. He would do best in a home with another dog. Not only does he love playing with other dogs, but another dog would teach him that people are ok. He would also do best in a home that is somewhat quiet with children over the age of 12.  Bubbly is up to date on vaccines. He is not currently neutered due to backlog from COVID but when he is able to be neutered, it will be paid for by Wag N' Purr Animal Rescue. If you are interested in little Bubbly, please complete the application below.

animal.description:
Meet Marvel!
Marvel is an owner surrender due to not liking to be disturbed from sleep by toddlers. Which in turn this is really most dogs. Marvel is a super sweet boy and terribly distraught after losing his family who had him for 7 years. He is slowly settling in but still really trying to understand what happened. Marvel is one of the sweetest boys you will meet that you would not believe is 7 years old. He does not look or act like a senior and very much a puppy in his own mind. He would do well with an active family that will love him. We do not suggest he be in a home with kids under 10 but as long as they are respectful he would do just fine. He loves attention and to cuddle and just wants to be where his family is. Marvel isn't quiet ready for adoption since he still needs to be neutered and microchipped but once those are completed he will be ready for his forever home! 

All animals adopted from us are fully vetted including spay/neuter, vaccines, microchip, heartworm test and deworming. Please email us at HookedOnDobies@gmail.com, visit our Facebook page www.facebook.com/savingdobermankind or webpage https://www.savingdobermankind.org to request an application, inquire about an adoption fee, or to learn more! 

We do require a completed adoption application to be submitted before discussing details of a specific Doberman. 

We DO NOT have a central location, out foster homes are located throughout our geographic region including CO, WY, NM and TX.

We strive to PROTECT the privacy of out fosters. ALL Doberman meet and greets are conducted in a neutral meeting location made by appointment only.

animal.description:
Finesse is a sweet girl that ended up abandoned in the middle of no where. We can't imagine why since she is doing so well in her foster home. She is good with other dogs and gets along with cats (although she's a bit fearful of them). She loves to be a lap dog and follows her foster mom around the house. She is doing well with potty training, and will need a home to provide a structured schedule to ensure she keeps that up. She also does well in the crate, but will bark so she would not do well in an apartment setting. If you are searching for a beautiful 30 lb lap dog and a fun girl to walk or run with, Finesse would love to meet you!

Please visit www.handsheartspaws.org for an adoption application

All of our dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, fecal tested, heartworm tested, and they are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home visit, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for this dog is $275___.

We do not REQUIRE a fenced in yard (some dogs DO REQUIRE a fence.  Decide what is best for each dog), we do REQUIRE a means of safe outside containment.  We do NOT adopt to homes that use invisible fencing.  Invisible fencing is NOT a safe means of outside containment.

We are willing to adopt out-of-state, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must travel to Omaha to complete the adoption. We do not transport or ship our dogs.

animal.description:
American Bulldog | Male | 1-2 years old | 90 lbs | Ontario Shelter Dog 
#emptyontarioshelters

Temperament: Affectionate, good-natured.
Activity Level: High. 
Vetting: Core vaccines (dh2pp, rabies & bordetella ), neutered, microchipped, dewormed, fecal - negative, 4dx bloodwork - negative (which means he doesn’t have Heartworm disease or tick borne diseases), on tick/heartworm and flea prevention. 
Housebroken? Yes.
Good with Dogs? Dudley is still learning how to regulate himself around dogs, especially males. He has proven that he can, with time and proper guidance, interact positively and would benefit with continued socialization. However, safety measures are necessary and this must be done only with extremely balanced dogs. Reactive dogs must be avoided at all times because of the possibility that Dudley, due to his size and strength, may escalate dog fights. For the same reason, Dudley should avoid dog parks, and get his socialization in more controlled environments (play-dates with appropriate dogs).
Good with Cats? No.
Good with Children? Yes, but we would advise against this. Dudley’s ideal home would be made up of people who can provide a calm environment with consistent boundaries and instructions.  
Any noted prey drive? Yes. He will take intense interest and may attempt to chase after squirrels, racoons, birds, cats, etc.
How do they respond to the outdoors? He is extremely over-stimulated, mostly by dogs, when on the leash and is currently working to better handle these encounters and is developing his skills on the leash. His ideal adopter will be somebody who can continue this work with him (in-person instructions from his current trainer will be provided). He is a delight in a fenced-in yard. He loves to play and is thrilled to be engaged with obedience training and training games. His ideal adopter should have an adequate backyard and enjoy physically and mentally engaging with him. He is a young boy and has the energy level to match and because his walks will be predominantly training focused, a yard is an essential resource for ensuring his exercise and enrichments needs are being fully met.
Busy Streets? Busy streets must be avoided, as they are not conducive to working through his issues on the leash. His ideal adopter, if in the city, will live on a reasonably quiet residential street with access to parks and pathways where distance can be maintained from dogs as he continues to develop his skills, focus and regulation.
What type of exercise do they get and how much? He gets 3-4 training walks a day (approximately 2 hrs total) and another 2-4 hours of outdoor play and training games.
How active are they? Very high energy. He can run and play for hours. He is quite calm in the house. He will get hyper if encouraged but his ideal adopter will promote calmness with him. He has learned to go settle in his place or crate when asked to.
Crate-Trained? Yes. Understands “Go to your crate” and can spend hours relaxing and/or enjoying a frozen KONG or appropriate chew. He sleeps beautifully in his crate throughout the night. He may bark slightly if he hears another dog barking, but will quickly respond to a clear ‘No” or “Enough”.
How do they respond to commands? Very well while indoors or focused in the backyard. He loves obedience training and the sky’s the limit with an adopter who enjoys training games and exercises.
How do they handle transit or car transportation? He is good in the car for the most part. He will become over-stimulated when he sees a dog but not unmanageable and is improving. Public transit should be avoided.
*We cannot guarantee breed mix nor age.
*Comes with 6 weeks of pet insurance valued at $500.

In summary, the best case scenario for Dudley would be a young, energetic individual or individuals who enjoy mentally and physically engaging with their dog. They should have a fair-sized backyard, live in a quiet neighbourhood and have prior experience with powerful breeds. Dudley is a truly lovely, good-natured young dog who just needs the right home and proper guidance to reach his incredible potential. If you think you might be just the family that he needs, please contact adopt@covetedcanines.org or fill out an application on our website: covetedcanines.org/apply-now

animal.description:
Meet sweet Cecelia. She is about 2 yrs old and was brought to us with her 10 puppies! She has been a wonderful mom, and the babies are weaned and getting ready for their forever homes. Cecelia is the perfect family dog, and she has incredible manners. She will walk up to any person, big or small, and sit to ask for a pet.  She would love to snuggle or lay at her owner's feet.  Her personality has blossomed as her puppies have weaned, and she is becoming more playful as well. 

Cecelia just tested positive for heartworms and will have to go through treatment. She will soon be ready to find her forever home too. SOAR will cover costs of heartworm treatment and medication needed for this treatment.

Adoption donation required. This covers altering, DAP series vaccinations to date of adoption, Bordetella Vaccination, Rabies vaccination if over four months, Microchip, Deworming, heartworm test (if over 8 months), monthly flea/heartworm prevention to date, grooming, full veterinary examination, and temperament evaluation. Please e-mail us for more information or go to our website https://soardogs.org/adoption-application for an application. Thank you very much! 


All SOAR dogs go through a ten-day quarantine period to ensure they are healthy, before being adopted. We do not operate on a first come first serve basis, but screen applicants in order to find the best fit for our adoptable dogs.

animal.description:
apunzel

Let down your hair!

This little fairytale is Rapunzel, a 14-week-old Bloodhound/Standard Poodle mix. Currently weighing in at 30 lbs, our little lady will grow to a good 90 lbs as an adult.

A delicate flower, Rapunzel needs a calm home, recommended older, calmer children only. She’s great with cats and other dogs if they too are calm.

Rapunzel will need a secure fenced in yard to get out and explore and someone home most of the day to keep her company and continue with her training.

The WAG team are already sprinkling their fairy dust and crate and potty training is coming along well. Although Rapunzel will soon sing out in that glorious Hound dawg way if she feels she’s been in the crate too long.

Happy, affectionate and lots of fun, Rapunzel just needs her happily ever after!

All of our animals are fully vetted which includes spay/neuter, up to date on vaccines, wormed, heartworm tested and treated if necessary, up to date on flea/tick/heartworm prevention and microchipped) prior to adoption.

To start the adoption process please copy the below link in your browser and complete the application.  NOTE:  please read our requirements located above the application.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSeotmh7qepR0mRvxSqy42yViQnllmR0-FKTFmUo2ANK4AXPaQ/viewform

animal.description:
Cypress is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Cypress is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~3 years 
Weight: ~53lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time to settle, but overall doing well with her crate-training. Has also done well with free roam while left solo.
Dog sociability: Friendly with dogs on walks
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Unknown, but she is very sensitive to loud noises/sudden movement so she would not be recommended for little kids. May do well with respectful teenagers that can read her body language and go slow.
Ideal home: Cypress is a sweet southern gal from Texas that is looking for a patient home that will allow her time to ease into her new surroundings. She is pretty scared outside on walks and prefers very quiet/suburban spaces. A backyard would be her dream! Having a dog pal in her home may also help to boost her confidence. 

Cypress is the sweetest, politest, little angel. Once she gets comfortable with you she's total snuggle bug. While her foster has been away, they have let her have access to the whole house and can see on cams that she mostly chills on the couch the entire time When it's time to go for a walk she puts her front paws on a seat and waits for you to put on her harness and coat. She is pretty sensitive to loud sounds and quick movements, so she would do best in a calm house in a quiet neighborhood. She'd probably benefit from living with another dog to show her that things aren't so scary. Car rides and string cheese are the way to this girl's heart!

Cypress tested positive for heartworm disease at her prior shelter and received treatment there in November. She will need to be on exercise restriction for the next 9 months until she can be retested for heartworm disease which should occur in August. If her 9 month retest comes back positive, OTAT will cover treatment at our Ellis Clinic. For information on heartworm disease, visit: onetail.org/heartworm

Cypress' adoption fee is 300. She is spayed, is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm positive. She will require booster vaccines at the adopter's expense. She will likely need a dental cleaning in the next year, and may require radiographs for worn teeth to determine if extraction is needed - also adopter responsibility.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
***Thank you for your interest in Magnificent Mutts and Meows. We hope everyone is saying safe during this challenging time. Due to the current regulations set forth by Governor Pritzker on group gatherings we will not be having adoption events until further notice. As an all foster based rescue this means that all meets will be by appointment only. Your whole family must be available to attend the meet as there will be no second meets scheduled to help limit contact between our team and the public. To help streamline the process please make sure your current pets are up to date, you have landlord/HOA approval, and that you are prepared to take the dog home with you immediately before submitting an application. Thank you & Please stay safe!***

Network to us from a rescue partner in the south CeCe just arrived. Approximately 2 years old! She is a laid back dog who can be playful at times. She is housetrained, and is working on leash skills. CeCe is not a fan of the crate, but once she gets in she just lays down. She is friendly and curious with all the dogs that walk by on walks, and she loves nothing more than lounging in the sun in the yard. Good with kids, cats unknown. She loves to be loved on and enjoys belly rubs!

Sadly, CeCe

arrived Heartworm positive so Magnificent Mutts will be treating her. After treatment she will go on to lead a normal happy life. Her only restriction is her adopters will need to keep her activity to

a minimum as he goes through the 30 days rest after Heartworm treatment.

Check back for more information and possible restrictions once he fully settles into foster care.

If you are interested in adoption, please complete the Application to Adopt which you can find on our website (
www.magnificentmutts.org
) No phone calls please. Emails only.

Adoption Donation $300 (cash only)

Please visit www.magnificentmutts.org for the online dog or cat application.

Adoption Fees*

Adult cats starting at $125, Kittens starting at $165.
Dogs/Puppies starting at $225 minimum
Prices subject to change, please contact for specific adoption donations.

WAG would recommend older children as Trojan can get rather excited at playtime! An active family would be ideal to burn off that energy and continue his basic manners training. A secure privacy fence is essential.

animal.description:
AJ is a six-year-old boxer/American bulldog mix that weighs 70 pounds. The previous owner took him to the shelter for euthanasia because he was in such poor condition due to neglect and abuse. The shelter contacted us to see if we could save him and we immediately drove to Solano and picked him up. After several months of being in foster care his wounds have healed up, he has gained 10 pounds and he is one happy boy!

AJ hops into the bathtub without any hesitation for his baths every week. He is crate trained and kennels up the minute you open the door.  He loves to go for car rides and if I go to work and don’t take him he is completely confused! AJ is one of the most affectionate dogs I have ever met, he thinks he is 10 pounds and belongs in your lap! He loves going for walks and behaves beautifully on the leash.

AJ does not bark or react to other dogs but we know that he is not good with other dogs. His new home must understand that he needs to be an only dog and he will never be able to go to a dog park.

We ran a full allergy panel on him to see what he might be allergic to and he is allergic to four types of grass. As his foster parents we are fortunate that we don’t have any grass, we have artificial lawn As well as bark and lots of patio areas.

If he goes to a home that is interested in having the allergy shots made for him so that he builds up a tolerance to the grasses he is allergic to that is certainly an option.

If you are interested in additional information please call or text Linea at 510-579-5850. Please do not email Petfinder!

animal.description: Hi there I'm Durango and I want to be your new best friend! My favorite place to be is right by your side. I am a playful puppy that loves to be the center of attention. I love to run and play with my foster sister, but listen well when called for. I am working hard on my potty training, and I potty right away when taken outside which is great this time of year! I like to be a good boy and I already know to sit before getting my food. I think I would be a great sidekick for anyone looking for a full time friend! I will play hard as long as you want, and then will snuggle right up with you at the end of the day. My sweet lab face is irresistible don't you think!? The "D Pups" came into rescue when they were just a couple weeks old, along with their sweet & beautiful mom, Daisybelle Fluffbottoms, when they became a homeless family and needed our help. Durango is a growing male Black Lab mix pup born approximately 10-23-20. He is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, given flea/tick preventive, dewormed & started on heartworm preventive. Adoption fee is $575 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. We rely strictly on adoption fees and donations to continue to save the lives of orphaned & abandoned pets; 100% goes towards their care. If interested in adopting one of our available dogs or puppies, please complete an online adoption application at https://dollyslegacyanimalrescue.org/adopt/ You will be contacted by our adoption coordinator via email after your application has been reviewed & approved to schedule an appointment.

animal.description:
Xena is a 6 month old pup looking for a home to call her own. She has a ton of energy and would love a home with a dog to play with. She is currently in a foster home where she is learning some basic commands and working on her house breaking. She loves people and is working on her leash skills. Her foster family is also crating her when she isn’t supervised. Xena is going to make a great addition to someone’s family. We do not cat test but her foster family reports no obvious prey drive when out in the yard so she may be willing to share her home with a cat. 
FOLLOW THESE INSTRUCTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED: 

To adopt, complete the application at tarnj.org/adopt

If you have any questions at all, please DO NOT use the PetFinder inquiry form as we do not respond to those. Questions should be sent to info@tarnj.org. 

An application is required before any meets are scheduled so the best way to be considered is to apply ASAP at tarnj.org/adopt.

We are all volunteer-run and do our best to respond to every application. If there is a match with your application, you should hear from us within 2-5 days. If you do not hear from us, please check your Junk folder or email us for an update.

animal.description:
Meet Elgin! Elgin is a fluffy 2 year old,  9 lbs. chug chihuahua - pug mix. He gets along great with other dogs, and people. He is new to the rescue. Be sure to check back as we get to know Elgin more!

If you’d like to meet Elgin, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestierescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 

Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 

Elgin’s adoption fee is $300 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.
We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 

We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human.
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

animal.description:
See Spot Run. See Spot Play. See Spot Give Kisses! Spot is a fun, friendly guy who is having a blast on the farm. He is enjoying making tons of new doggy friends and has quickly become best friends with several new playmates who he loves to wrestle with. Between matches, you can find Spot soaking up attention from volunteers. Spot is young about a year old and still has some of that playful puppy energy and loves playing with toys. He would be a great running buddy or hiking partner, supplemented with trips to the doggy park where he could make even more doggy friends! He walks well on a leash and knows to do his potty outside, but otherwise lacks much more in the ways of formal training. Spot has all the makings of a great, loyal companion with just a little structure and guidance to show him the way. While Spot is enjoying his time at Saving Grace, we would really love to See Spot find a furever home!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
This little angel is Mayham. He is a very special boy to us and needs a very special home. Hammie is a dog who has been  repeatedly let down by people. When  we got Ham he had been dumped in the county and had been running stray for several months and during that time He had been repeatedly pepper sprayed by the mail man.  Eventually when he wouldn't go away one of the people in the area called us about him. When we picked him up he was very thin and he trusted no one. With a little time and effort he slowly started to trust us. He has been with us for a while and is such an amazing dog who will allow anything from the people he loves and trust. He enjoys cuddling and being held.  He can still be shy with new people but once you have gained his trust you have a friend for life. Mayham is  such a big baby in every way. He does great with other dogs and kids too. Ham is a  boy who needs a patent home that is willing to give him the time and love he deserves. Ham is a athletic boy who can clear a 4 ft fence. He enjoys going out on walks and then coming home and crashing in the blankets. Hammie is a smart boy too and has graduated form obedience class. He is about 6-8 years old

If you are interested in Ham please fill out this form https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdpiuLi8g3wkOBxGH6G_ek2PHQUBrWSIf90c3EdtpcD0gj4mQ/viewform?usp=sf_link

May ham requires a secure 6 ft fence, a cat free home, and frequent updates and pics. 

Adoption fee is $190
The adoption fee includes:
*Spaying/Neutering
*Booster vaccine
*Dewormings
*Rabies vaccine
*Microchip
*treated for fleas
* Marion City tags
* 20% off at Art in motion
* $5 off at petlink
* $20 off a 6-week training course

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.German Shepherd dogs, as well as the other herding breeds that we have in rescue, are highly active, energetic, working breeds. They require considerable vetting, exercise, socialization, training, leadership and mental stimuli in order to be well-adjusted, well-balanced, and well-mannered dogs. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings in order to work on his/her leash skills, manners, and social skills. These breeds make great additions to active families who will pamper them, but who will also work with them, as they are smart dogs who need leadership, structure, plenty of activity and mental stimulation. If you are new to German Shepherds (and other herding breeds), please research the breed to make sure this is the dog for you. We ask that you consider the time and financial commitment that your German Shepherd (or other herding breed) dog will require before applying for one. Please review the section on our website (www.heartlandgsrescue.org) 'Is a HUGS Dog Right for You?' for additional information. Emma is a sweet, goofy, playful young gal. She loves walks and playing with toys. She knows 'sit,' 'kennel up,' and is working on 'down' and 'drop.' Emma is very treat motivated and is a smart girl. She is working hard on her manners and greeting visitors without jumping up. She enjoys playing with the dogs in her foster home, as she is full of puppy energy. She loves being around the humans in her foster home as well, and likes getting lots of attention from them. She also really enjoys going for walks and playing outside with her foster parents. She is working on her leash manners as well. Since Emma is just a young pup, she will thrive in an active forever home.
Like all German Shepherds, this sweet girl would make a great addition to an active home that will provide the love, structure, good leadership, activity and mental stimulation that she needs. Because of that, Emma's ideal owner will have prior GSD, or similar breed experience. Emma would do fine as an only dog, or with a patient/mellow dog her size. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, please remember that you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings, in order to provide sufficient stimulation, ward off boredom, and work on leash skills, and manners. Emma's adoption fee is $400, all of which goes back into offsetting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm testing if old enough (treated if positive), and microchipped. Learn more about the adoption process and requirements, and apply at: http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption. Please review the information in the 'About Us', 'Important Considerations' and 'Adopt' sections on our website menu, as it contains useful information about the breed, adoption fees, the adoption process and our requirements, and how meeting the dogs works.

animal.description: Sweet Rosie is approx 4-5yrs old and weighs about 68lbs.  This darling girl was used as a breeding machine, with her last litter only 9 wks old.  They have been weaned and now she can find a home of her own.  Luckily, she’ll be spayed soon and will be able to find a family that will love and dote on her, like she so desperately desires.  She still needs a few more weeks before she can be spayed so we are looking for a foster home until her surgery.  She will then be available for adoption. After all she’s been through, she’s not interested in having other animals in the home.  She is wonderful with people though, and would love to have a home that has plenty of time to share.  She does fine on a leash , although she’s a very easy going girl that would be happy just relaxing with her people or hanging out in the fenced yard.  She is crate trained so can be left alone for a reasonable amount of hours.  She must have a 6ft securely fenced yard and kids must be over 10yrs old.  During foster, all supplies will be provided.

animal.description:
Luka is a very sweet special needs tiny chi, about 10 years old we think and only 7lbs! 

He came to us from another shelter where he was found unable to walk, partially paralyzed and dragging his hind legs. It appears to be an old injury and nothing to be done to fix it at this point but he's a happy little guy not in pain and loves to be carried. He doesn't have control of his bladder and bowels and needs his bladder expressed several times daily (he is very easy and tolerant for it!) and needs someone experienced with caring for special needs pups like him. 

If you are interested in opening your home to this sweetheart please submit an application from our website. He's in the process of getting a full medical work-up with our veterinary team- he has a heart murmur that will require more testing and desperately needs a dental as his teeth are rotting and falling out! Primary Color: Chocolate Secondary Color: White Age: 9yrs 10mths 0wks
