animal.description:
A sweet dog, to be your loyal best friend, a companion that will always have your back and stay by your side, well that's just the stuff our boy Legend is made of! Legend is a 1-year-old lab mix currently weighing about 65 lbs but in need of gaining some weight. It would appear Legend may have not always know the kindness the world has to offer, but that doesn't stop him from seeing the best in people and taking every opportunity he can to be adored. He is a sweet boy who likes to be close to you. Legend has been settling in fine and the farm and gets along with his doggy friends, but he really is looking for that special person he gets to call his very own. He sleeps well in a crate overnight and knows to go potty outside. He may not know a lot in the ways of fancy tricks, but he promises to be a quick study and hang on to your every word. So get in your adoption request so you can come on down to the farm and meet this sweet boy!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

animal.description:
Izzy is a 1 year old Anatolian Shepherd mix. She weighs 66 pounds. Unfortunately, her owners were no longer able to keep her and surrendered her to the shelter. This beautiful girl is looking for an active home where she will get plenty of exercise and attention. She is super playful and loves running around and playing with her toys. She is super outgoing with people and loves everyone she meets but she is still working on her manners. Because of her activity level, she would do best in a home without small children. She had previously lived with kids. She is dog friendly, in fact the shelter used her to test other dogs to see how they were with dogs.  Izzy walks well on a leash.  Izzy loves to go for car rides and is crate trained.  She absolutely loves the snow and the cold doesn't seem to phase her.  

If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application on our website:                          https://.barkdogfarm.rescuegroups.org/forms/ 

Before applying be sure you have thoroughly researched Anatolians.  They are a live stock guardian dog that can become overly protective and cannot be off leash much like great pyrs. They are not a breed for inexperienced owners.  You WILL NOT train them to boundaries.  
Please be sure all family members are in agreement to adopting and your family is ready to bring dog home now. 
Applicants must be at least 21 years old. 
A volunteer will be in touch to discuss your application and the dog to determine if it is a good match. Your vet and two references will be called.  A virtual home visit done. Once approved a meet and greet at the farm will take place.  If all are in agreement and the animal has received its NH health certificate an adoption contract will be signed and adoption fee paid.  
Adoption fees for dogs are $450. for adults over 12 months, $500 for puppies 12 months and younger.  Fees for seniors, special needs or harder to place dogs will be determined by our Board of Directors.
 All dogs will be altered when adoption is finalized, up to date on age appropriate core vaccines, negative for parasites, heart worm and lyme tested if 6 months or older, microchipped and have a current health certificate.  
Proof of a basic obedience course completed is part of our adoption contract within six months. 
Our descriptions are based on shelter evaluations, input from foster homes and interactions with our volunteers therefore are in no way a guarantee of temperment. 

! Please know we practice Covid-19 guidelines for mask wearing and social distancing.  Only approved applicants are allowed to meet our dogs outdoors at this time. Please email barkingdogfrm@gmail.com with any questions.

New COVID-19 Adoption Procedures: The first step is to fill out an application on our website. Petfinder inquiries are not considered an application. Adoptions are conducted on a best-match basis. If we feel you are a great match for an animal you have applied for, we will reach out to you regarding the next steps to adoption.

-- There are no animals at the shelter and the shelter itself is closed. --

 If you're interested in a pet:
Visit our website and fill out an application. We will send a response email with what to expect and be in touch if we will be moving forward in the process with you. Please be patient and understand response times are currently a bit lengthy. We cannot expedite the process if you call and email to follow up.

* Please note that our adoptable pets are all in foster right now, so if we move forward with scheduling a meet-and-greet appointment (dogs only), the foster will bring the pet to us for you to meet. Due to this, you will be limited to meeting one pet during your appointment. Thank you for your understanding!
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Check out adoptable dogs and cats on our website: spcasc.org

 Complete the Adoption Profile
Once you've found a well-matched furry friend, please complete our Adoption Profile form on our website. You must be at least 21 years old to adopt.

 Housing
If you rent, please provide a copy of your lease or a letter from your landlord that states you can have a pet(s). Landlord letters can be presented in person or by email and must be accompanied by a copy or photo of the homeowner's ID. If you own, we will verify ownership through our database, you do not need to bring any documentation.

It's important that any current canine companions enjoy your new friend as much as you do. We facilitate dog-to-dog introductions outside our main shelter, on leash. For your own dog's safety, we ask that you do not bring him or her into the shelter. If we move forward with your application and you apply for a dog and already have one, you will be asked to bring your current dog to meet your new potential dog to do a meet-and-greet, then take the dog home for a 7-day "trial."

Age: ~2yr / Weight: ~60lbs

I'm TROOPER!

I was transferred from another shelter and am still settling in here, but here's what the SCSPCA knows about me so far:

 I am very friendly with everyone I've met so far

 I'm a very boisterous, happy, active boy

 People are great!

 I've been doing great with dog pals here at the shelter

 I love to entertain myself when no one's watching, so I would love lots of tough toys I can chew on!

 Cats and small dogs are unknown to me

If you're interested in adopting me, fill out an application on the website!

animal.description:
Bonnie is a  Border Collie mix that was rescued this Spring from a hoarding situation. She has healed and learned so much since being in care! She is now crate trained, and loves going on walks with her foster mom and confident big brother canine. She is a shy girl and understandably so, considering the situation she grew up in. She continues work with her foster mom daily and was recently seen by our dog trainer, as we want to continue to build her confidence while ensuring her safety. She is fearful in new situations so patience and leadership by her human is needed. She loves playing with her canine foster family and also is fine with the kitties in the home. She will need a home with a secure fence and another social dog to help guide her. She would do best with only older children in the home, who will be patient and give her time to get to know them. We are committed to her transition and want her to find a wonderful forever family . Would you like to foster to adopt? We would like to help guide her transition to a new home with some help from her foster mom and our trainer.

* Another confident dog in the home
* No children under 15
* A house with a secure yard. (Due to her shy nature she will not be available for adoption into an apartment.)
* Bonnie would do best in a calm smaller household.

animal.description:
Breed: Yellow Lab/ Australian Cattle Dog
Age: 7 years old
Weight: 43 lbs.
Good with dogs: Yes
Good with cats: Not tested
Good with kids: Older kids, afraid of loud noises and sudden movements
Energy Level: Medium/High

Available for Adoption: Currently accepting application.
Your application must be approved prior to meeting any dog.

Chase came to Double Dog in mid-October of 2020 from the Philadelphia shelter. He had been time stamped due to cage stress and reactivity in the shelter environment. We decided to take a chance on Chase and bring him into rescue.  It was immediately evident that Chase had been abused. He was terrified of a slip leash, head shy, fearful of loud noises, and generally speaking, a complete bag of canine nerves. It is believed that his tail was intentionally broken as well.

Chase has made tremendous progress with the help of a professional trainer and dedicated fosters. He is extremely intelligent and now knows multiple commands. Being highly food motivated as well as a super smart pup has helped make training go well for Chase. 

Chase is engaging, handsome and as mentioned, SO smart! He would thrive in an environment where someone is most often home. Chase has excellent house manners and expects to be crated at bedtime...this helps with the structure that Chase needs. Chase would do best in a home without children. Canine siblings are fine, but he would also be happy as an only pup as well. Chase gravitates to men, but mainly just needs a loving, but firm and dog savvy family that is active and will include him on hikes and walks as part of his daily routine. Chase has been through a great deal in his life; he has proven that with love and time, any obstacle is surmountable. Chase has made such amazing progress in the few months he has been with us and now needs a committed and loving family to bring him full circle. 

If you think you could be that person to give Chase the love he deserves, please contact Summer at summer.doubledogrescue@gmail.com.

animal.description:
6 year old hound mix Okra has a bright and affectionate personality. She loves to meet new people and is wonderful with other dogs, large and small. If you have an unruly pup at home, she would be a perfect dog to help teach it manners - hers are impeccable! She:
•	Is house trained
•	Walks nicely in a harness
•	Is 35 pounds
•	Enjoys going for car rides
•	Loves outdoor activities
•	Is medium to high energy
Still spunky and silly, Okra enjoys stuffed toys and loves to play ball! She is working through some separation anxiety and needs an owner who is mostly home or another dog to keep her company. She is an unwaveringly loving and loyal companion; once you are her person, there will be nothing more important in the world than you! 

Okra is currently undergoing treatment for heartworms and is expected to make a full recovery. For more information on the treatment process and how HLCR will assist, please call our office at 830.693.0569.

Okra is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and heartworm negative. 

For more information about Okra or our shelter please call us at (830) 693-0569 or visit our website at highlandlakescaninerescue.org 

If you would like to schedule a meet and greet with Okra or any of our dogs, please fill out an application at highlandlakescaninerescue.org/application-for-adoption

animal.description:
Cassie is a sweet, fun spitfire in the making. When Cassie arrived at the kennel, she was very fearful, and it seemed like she had not had a lot of socialization in her young life. But she has slowly been opening up with people, and has been revealing the bright, curious, feisty young lady within! Once she gets to know a person, she will happily treat herself to some lap time or snuggles in between exploring on walks and play time. It seems like she will be a real whiz with fetch with a little more practice! Cassie would benefit from a patient, experienced home to help her to continue building her confidence and learning about the world. She is currently still very anxious and fearful (and so somewhat spastic) around other dogs and may benefit from being able to be the only dog in the house - or at least having very gradual intros. Cassie is estimated to be under a year old, still very much an older puppy, and weighs 36 lbs.
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
Given how Tina first came to our notice, it is truly a wonder when you see the dog she is today. Our rescue partner in West Virginia reached out to us in April of 2019 about a feral, heavily pregnant dog that had came in as a stray. Terrified out of her mind, the staff there knew that they needed help with this dog who was ready to give birth soon. We came, and along with a few other dogs, brought Tina back to our shelter. The next few months were spent helping this new mom take care of her puppies (although she did not need much help!) and then once all of her puppies were in foster and then adopted we turned our focus to Tina. 

In the last year and a half, we have been constantly amazed by the progress Tina has made. She had never experienced what we assume all dogs have done; walking on a leash, eating from a food bowl, being around people, all were foreign to her. What has aided Tina tremendously is the fact that she is so dog-friendly and tolerant. Tina thrives off the companionship and camaraderie of other dogs and by being around them she slowly started mimicking and picking up on things that they do. Her first friend at our shelter was Legend and as roommates, he helped show her a thing or two about the best parts of being a dog and what to enjoy in life. Now she is roomies with Raven, who has shown Tina that snacks and toys are the ultimate and that you have to make sure if you are not playing you are snacking!

By no means has Tina completely transformed into what we would consider a normal dog but she has certainly made strides towards something like it. The first time she rolled over and gave belly to our Shelter and Behavior Assistant Leslie we all collectively smiled and gasped a bit! An ideal home for Tina would be one with a lot of patience and determination that has at least one other dog if not more. She would definitely need a fenced-in yard as she is not the type to just go out the back and come right back inside (baby steps!). We cannot wait to see what strides Tina continues to make and we cannot wait to see what her future has in store.

Heartworm negative, neutered, chipped, and utd on all shots, we think he is 4 years old. No cats, birds small dogs, other male dogs or small kiddos. He does great with altered large females. He has to have a very secure 6ft privacy fence. No dog parks for him. No apartments.
If you feel like this sweet boy would fit your family please apply at Someone2love.org.

He does know sit and shake. A dog door would be great he just needs to be taught.

animal.description:
Daisy is a 1 year old chihuahua mix female who was surrendered by her family in January of 2021.   She lived on the Navajo Reservation in Crownpoint, NM and her family was unable to provide basic veterinary care for her, so they surrendered her because they knew she could have a better life somewhere else.  
Daisy weighs just over 15 lbs. and her mother was a purebred chihuahua who died during the birth of Daisy's litter.  We're not sure who her dad was.  
We are looking for a home for Daisy that is quiet and patient and can give her a safe place to settle in to once she is adopted.  She takes a little while to warm up to new people and environments, but once she does she is very sweet.  She is shy and skittish until she settles in to a new environment.  We think she would love to have one or two adults in her home, and that she would get used to other dogs once she was comfortable.  She lived with other dogs on the reservation.  Daisy bonds really well with "her person" and is sweet and loving and happy around them, but needs time and patience to be comfortable around others.  
Daisy is spayed and current on her vaccinations.  Her adoption fee is $200.  Please call us at 970-749-1968 for more information on Daisy.

Meet our resident big hunk Nene! 
Nene came to us after his family needed help finding him a home that had more space.

Nene is 7 years old, EXTREMELY sweet, sensitive, and gentle.. he truly just seeks out love and attention more than anything in the world.

Nene loves going on car rides, and walks and didnt come to us leash trained so that's been a work in progress, but boy does he love to get out and explore!
Nene has been kennel training as he had never been kennel trained, nor was he house broken but now that hes neutered progress has been made in that department.

Nene longs to be part of something, part of a family, part of your day, his heart is as big as his body all 110 lbs of it!

Nene comes with free training and is looking for a foster or foster to adopt home where he can be loved.

Bo is a 11 year old German Shepherd mix who weighs about 64 pounds.  Bo is house trained. This somewhat older boy has been with his owner since he was two, but sadly she recently passed away, and now he needs a new home in which to spend his golden years.

Bo enjoys spending time in his fenced yard (he likes his time outdoors, but if there's a thunderstorm he'd like to be inside!).  He'd do best in a home without cats as he will likely go after them.  He got along with the female Lab that shared his home, but he seems a little nervous around other dogs.  He is really good with children.   When he's had enough of their attention, he will just walk away.  Bo loves walks.  This laid back affectionate boy will appreciate your loving attention and can't wait to meet your loving family.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lulu was rescued from the San Bernardino City Shelter. She came into the shelter extremely emaciated and was there for a couple months. The shelter reached out to us, because they couldn't believe such a sweet girl hadn't been rescued yet. That is when Lulu became a Cause dog!Lulu is very sweet and friendly. She's a big goofy girl who loves her belly rubs and will roll onto her back for anyone. She's also very smart, knows how to sit, and is completely house trained. She has never had an accident in her foster home. Her teeth are in rough shape, due to possibly chewing on electrical cords at some point and possible neglect. Despite this, she's as happy as can be and doesn't have any trouble eating kibble. She has a surprising amount of energy for an older dog, but also prefers to relax for most of the day. She gets along with non confrontational dogs. We haven't had the chance to observe her with children, but think she would be just fine. We also haven't been able to observe her with cats yet, but will be testing her soon.At the time Lulu was spayed, she also had a mammary tumor removed. It was biopsied and found to be low grade cancerous. However, the vet was very happy with how clean the removal was and is hopeful that no more growths will form. Lulu was also x-rayed to check for other growths and there were none. Still, any adopter would have to be vigilant of any lumps that form and the vet recommended an x-ray every 6-8 months, just to be extra cautious.
Lulu would love a warm bed and lots of love to spend her senior years. If that could be you, please apply to adopt our girl Lulu!

animal.description:
Say hello to Bella!

She is a 5 year old Pit Bull mix who weighs about 65 pounds. Bella is a super sweet and loving girl who can't get enough attention. The quickest way to Bella's heart is by grabbing a toy and playing with her until she's tuckered out. She is a gregarious girl who loves to run around and then cuddle up on the couch to snuggle. She is still adjusting to life at the shelter and will take patience and plenty of love while she's adjusting to her new forever home. With the right dog, she shows potential to live with another resident dog, but she wouldn't mind being the only dog in the home either! Bella can be a bit sensitive to new situations and can become overwhelmed without the reassurance of her favorite people. Due to her initial sensitivity, if Bella's forever home have children in it they would need to need to be age 16 and older. Bella has a heart of gold and can't wait to find her new best friend. 

If Bella looks like the pup for you, give us a call at 234-212-9843 to learn more about her and schedule an appointment to meet her!

Say hello to Eileen! 

She is a 4 year old Pitbull/Bulldog mix who weighs about 65 pounds. This sweet girl can be a little shy when first meeting new people, but with the help of some tasty treats she warms up well! She can be sensitive to new situations, but does well with the help of her favorite people by her side! She has been in a foster home for over a month now and has been doing great adjusting to a new place. Her foster family has a young child and multiple dogs that Eileen has done great with. If it's the right fit, she shows potential to live with children under 10 as well as another resident dog. When she's not napping, Eileen is a playful girl who loves to play ball. When she's feeling playful she'll even pick up the ball and throw it to you when she wants to fetch! Eileen is a super sweet and loving girl who can't wait to find her forever home.

If Eileen sounds like the pup for you, give us a call at 234-212-9843 to learn more about her and schedule an appointment to meet her!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Rowdy is a Basset Hound/Spaniel mix with an approximate birthday of October 1st, 2009. He's a sweet old man that loves two things: sleeping and food.

Rowdy, an 11 year old deaf pup, spends about 75% of his time napping. (Check the pictures to see some interesting napping spots he has.) It is pretty hard to wake him up so we love to watch movies with him on the couch while he sleeps. The hound in him will wake up whenever we are cooking, however. He may watch you eat, but he will never steal off your plate (especially since he is 1 1/2 feet tall)! His hound side can also come with a loud bark used when he is hungry or needs to potty, so a lack of kids with little ears may be ideal. He really reserves his bark for communication so it's easy to tell when he needs something!

He's got quite a few quirks that make him special. He shakes his head and his ears make a whopping sound whenever he wakes up, his eyebrows give him an extra level of sass, and one of his ears is longer than the other. Rowdy is friendly with other dogs and has not met another cat yet. He doesn't react to barking dogs or loud people (obviously!) and usually just likes to sniff when he interacts with dogs. He goes where he wants and is just enjoying his life.

One of our favorite things to do is take a walk with him after dinner time. When we get out, he is usually out for the rest of the night. He has a bad hip, so walking helps strengthen his legs and gets the afternoon energy boost out. The home he goes to needs to have NO stairs. He has fallen a few times and it is too hard on him. Despite this, Rowdy thinks he is as agile as a young dog and will jump of couches and beds with little hesitation. He is so sweet and ready for a loving home!

**He is up to date on all core vaccinations (rabies/distemper), is microchipped and neutered. He has, however, tested positive for Ehrlichia, a tick illness. Nothing needs to be done with this unless he shows symptoms of the disease. Treatment is antibiotics for a month each time he has a flare up. Some dogs go their whole life with no issues and some need meds. It just depends on the dog.Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

Breed and temperament determination: Wags & Whiskers Animal Rescue attempts to determine breed and temperament using a combination of looks, information provided to us at intake, and our experience with the animal while in our Rescue. We do not guarantee this determination.

animal.description:
Mirror mirror on the wall, who is the very best girl of them all?

Hi I'm Kora! Some of you might remember my babies known as Kora's Kids. My foster mom picked me up when I was very pregnant from a shelter in Texas last year. I gave birth to 11 beautiful babies on Mother's Day 2020.
They have all grown up and left me but I stayed behind because I had those nasty heartworms. I am happy to report I am now heartworm free. 

I have been in foster care for so long and have payed the ultimate price for having a crappy owner. Not spayed or on heartworm preventative! To top it off we found out that I had a had torn ACL needing surgery. That was another setback but now I am completely healed now and can run like the wind. Now I am ready to find my family.

I am a Border Collie mix about 3-4 yrs. old and weigh 45 lbs. I love to play so another playful dog would be great.
I am completely housebroken and crate trained and walk well on a leash.

I love to lay my head on your lap and be told how beautiful I am.

I love kids but absolutely hate cats.
I am a very aware of strange noises and will alert you but I am not an obsessive barker. I am the perfect package.
Thank you for taking time to read my story!

Kora Jean (my foster Mom calls me that)

If you are interested in any of our dogs, please complete our online adoption application:

http://www.lifesaverssp.dreamhosters.com/adoption-applicat/

We will conduct a phone interview, check references and then a home check. This helps us to match a dog with their potential adopter. The adoption fee is $350.00 for adults and $450.00 for puppies under one year which includes spay/neutering, up-to-date age appropriate vaccinations, flea/tick & heartworm preventative and a health certificate. We foster our dogs in homes, not in shelters. This allows us to get to know the dogs temperaments in order to match them to a home. This also allows us to get the dogs ready to live in their forever homes! All dogs coming from the south have been quarantined for two weeks and fully vetted before traveling to New England!

For more info please email Lifesaversapps@outlook.com OR visit our website:

http://www.lifesaverssp.org/

animal.description:
Yakko is a very sweet and goofy boy. He’s about 1-2 years old, but still acts like a puppy. He loves balls, squeaky toys and bones. Yakko is happy to see everyone and tries to give hugs. Yakko thinks he’s a lap dog and has no concept of personal space. If you chill on the couch, he is chilling out on you. If you are petting him and stop, he paws you to keep going. Yakko is working on learning commands such as; come, sit stay and no. He is crate trained and will voluntarily go into the crate when he’s not getting attention. Yakko is not quite housebroken, but he’s learning quickly and doing well. He is very treat motivated. He does pull on the leash when walking, but is working on that also. Yakko does well with cats, mostly ignores them. He does well with other dogs his size and smaller, but avoids dogs bigger than him. Yakko has been on a few walks and is cautious about his surroundings. Yakko does gobble his food and needs a slow feeder. Because of his size and jumping up, no children under the age of 13.   If you would like to meet this dog please call Heather at 630-615-1745.  The adoption fee is $225.

- age appropriate vaccinations:  Bordetella, DH(L)PP, rabies

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Stella is a 30-35 lb. hound mix with an estimated date of birth of 3/3/2015. She is a medium-sized, strong and slender type dog who loves to run outdoors and chill indoors in a cozy spot nearby her people.

Stella is a sweet, smart, sensitive, loving, and low-maintenance dog. House-trained with great and predictable potty habits. Sleeps in as late as you want to sleep in. She is shy with strangers and will bark fearfully at new people sometimes, but once she warms up to someone with a little time and space, she is mellow and trusting. She's very well-behaved and aware of when things are off limits-she's careful to make sure it's okay to jump up on furniture, won't touch the trash even if food is sticking out of it, and when she needs something, whether going potty or for a walk, she lets you know--sometimes by putting a paw or two on you and staring at you (as in one of the pics here), or by doing a little march with her front paws.

She knows some basic commands. She likes her kennel, but she'll definitely take snuggling in a bed or on a sofa with a person over that. She loves sitting next to a heater. She's fine left alone in the house un-kenneled. She isn't very interested in toys or fetch and doesn't chew on anything.

Stella has lived her whole life with another dog, but in her later years she started fighting more frequently with the other dog, possibly for dominance, so she would be better as an only dog. She will bark at noises, so probably best for her to live without shared walls. She is mellow and happy when things are predictable but has anxiety with storms and fireworks, and she doesn't like car rides.

On walks, she pulls on her leash sometimes and barks/lunges at other dogs and passing cars, but even in a short time she's gotten better at not pulling, so she might just need getting more comfortable with her person and her neighborhood. She is medium energy, and with me, was fine with a short 15-30 minute walk daily and a couple of potty breaks. Given the chance, she loves to sprint at breakneck speed across a frozen lake!

She's fine with children although she seems aware of the pack hierarchy. She ignored my younger child for a few days and then was as loving with him as everyone else.

If you think Stella would be a good fit for your home, please apply!

animal.description:
**PLEASE READ GIA'S BIO THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING. ALL REQUIREMENTS MUST BE MET IN ORDER TO BE CONSIDERED.**



Gia is our gorgeous 4 year old female Terrier mix who is approximately 18lbs of adorableness! Gia came to us as an owner surrender who never spayed/neutered his pets and she ended up having a couple litters. He contacted us when he was overwhelmed with dogs and surrendered all 5 dogs to us. We have found them all amazing homes, but Gia is still looking for her happy ever after. This little lady LOVES to talk, boy does she love to talk. In rescue we call it "bark talking." She's a good listener though and minds well. We do not want Gia to go into a home that does not have another dog. She seems to only connect and do well with male dogs that are sweet like her. She is not great with bigger dogs, so a dog her size or smaller would be perfect! Although she is amazing with everyone she meets including children, we want her in a home with kids that are 12 years old or older. Gia can be a flight risk and she's fast so for her safety we are requiring a 3ft doggy gate at the front door inside the home as a preventative measure when the door is opened/closed. This is contractual regardless if you have a secure screen door or a fenced in front yard....a 3ft dog gate is required. Gia doesn't necessarily need a home with a yard, but please note that she is in a home now with a yard and outdoor access all day and she still goes potty in the house occasionally. It's not that she isn't potty trained, but she just needs constant work in that department. This sweet girl really needs a dog savvy home that is patient, kind, and loving and will give her all the time she needs to acclimate. She has been in foster for almost 2 years, so an adjustment to a new home is going to be very hard on her. Once she opens up to you and feels safe, you will see her true personality come out! She is a very loving girl who thrives for attention and LOVES to be next to you! You must be ok with allowing your pets on the furniture including the couch and your bed. We can't allow her to be crated. Gia had a very sad young life and we want to make sure that the rest of it is absolutely THE BEST! 

For Gia, we are requiring at least 2 meet/greets before we even decide to go the next step. A meet/greet will be held in the Torrance area where everyone in the home including your dog will come down and spend some time with her to see if this could be a match.


WE ONLY ADOPT IN LOS ANGELES AND SURROUNDING AREAS AS AN IN PERSON HOME CHECK AND TRIAL PERIOD ARE REQUIRED.

Gia's adoption fee is $500



Gia is spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped.

If you meet all the requirements and would like an application, please contact us at 310-990-2020 or at Gina@theforgottendog.org

animal.description: Hello my name is Lucille. I am a 1 year old Hound mix that weighs approx. 50-55lbs. I am a sweet girl that loves to go for walks and spend time with my people. I have some doggy friend but a meet and greet is suggested if you have other dogs in the home. I am not suggested with cats or small mammals. I do not like to be left alone in the yard for extended periods of time as I will seek out people. I am leash trained and crate trained. My adoption fee is $125. animal.description:
Todd is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Todd is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~1.5 years
Weight: ~69lbs
Housebroken: Working on it! He needs to be on a strict schedule
Crate trained: Hasn't been left alone for very long due to COVID and will benefit from an adopter willing to continue to work on this. 
Dog sociability: Leash reactive/frustrated in our care meaning he barks/lunges/pulls at other dogs. He is very strong and requires a confident handler. 
Cat sociability: Not a match
Kids: Lives with kids under 10 and has been doing great!
Ideal home: Todd will do best in a quieter neighborhood where he can work on his leash skills! A backyard would be his dream. 

Todd is a big, super-friendly guy that loves all people! He enjoys giving kisses and snuggling with you all day long. He absolutely loves to be pet and will let you know when he's not ready for his massage to be over yet by gently nudging your hand for more. His favorite pastimes are chasing squirrels, playing with tennis balls and fluffy toys. At the end of the day he likes to curl up with a good bone and watch The Great British Baking Show. Todd will do best with a handler in a more low-key area that is committed to working on training!

Todd's adoption fee is 300. He is neutered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
I’m 3 years old and about 38 lbs.

Hey there families!  My name is Josie.  Do you need an addition to your family that is full of love and snuggles?  That’s me!  Being in my current foster home I have learned that I can be at peace and move at my own pace.  I am on low-activity at the moment since I am going through heartworm treatments but I am not letting that get me down.  I am the curious kind, observant, and love to have some quick spurts around the yard.  I know I must get my rest and without having to be told I come right in and lay down.  I like snuggling up to the humans, adult or child (9 and 14), and with the other fur friends (dogs, not cat tested within current foster home).  I have been doing very well with relieving myself outside and have not had any accidents within my foster home.  I am great in the crate.  I have shown no signs of resource guarding when it comes to food and will share whatever I have.  I have not shown an interest in toys just yet nor have I made a peep vocally.  I do pretty well on the leash but will get even better over time.  I am just an easy going gal that just wants love and comfort.

Medical Note:  I am heartworm positive.  I had my first injection treatment on 1/19 and I will need another in about a month.  You can adopt me but you will need to be able to transport me to the vet for my treatment in February.  

You can still come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturdays. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Looking for a forever home, Meet Coco!  We are helping her elderly family find her a great family as they are having to relocate due to health issues.  Coco will be up to date on all vaccinations before she goes to her new family.  She is microchipped and spayed.  Please apply at www.makrescue.org unless you are already approved.  Her adoption fee will be a donation of your choice.

Dog's Name: Coco
Location: Kansas City, MO
Neutered/Spayed? Spayed
Age/Birthdate: 9 years - 10/5/2011
Reason for surrendering: Moving out of state/health concerns
What is her energy level (low, medium, high)? Very High!
Typical exercise she receives? Short walks only to potty.
Kind of fencing she requires? Has never jumped any fence.
Training? (house, crate, leash, potty, hunting, obedience - commands she knows) house trained, crate. Commands: Sit, lay down.
Has she ever shown any aggressions - toys, food, other animals, children, people? No. Jumps on people as greeting. Mouths hands a bit but does not bite down.
How does she act around dogs? Cats? Kids? Playful with dogs, excellent with cats. Kids, unknown but would most likely knock down smaller kids on accident.
What is a typical day like for her? Potty every 3-4 hours. Kept inside the majority of the day.
Any other important information we should know? She is very hyper around new people and in new environments. Does not like nails trimmed, but she'll chew on her nails. She is good with her owners but gets real anxious/over excited in new environments, she won't rest, paces and has trouble with her potty training.

animal.description:
Jazzy is a pretty girl and is very intelligent (already knows some tricks) and is loyal.  She is around 3 years old and weighs around 50 lbs.  She loves to play with toys and loves being with people.  She is desperate to find her own person to attach herself too.  She is in a foster home and follows her foster mom everywhere around the house.  Although she enjoys playing, if you are busy, she will go lay down or chew on a Nylabone to entertain herself.

Her foster home has a female dog and Jazzy has been dominant with her and tries to guard her toys from her.  Jazzy would like all of the dog attention on her.  For these reasons, a home with not other dogs (or maybe a submissive male) is needed and no children under 12 years old please.  Jazzy has not been cat tested.

A secure fenced yard (no invisible fences please) is preferred.

Jazzy is housebroken, spayed and current on vaccinations.  She has not been crated at her foster home and is not destructive when left alone.

Please email is you have any questions about sweet Jazzy!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Lottie was found as a stray and, after a lengthy search for owners proved unsuccessful, she found her way to Paw Placement. This sweet girl is currently in a loving foster home where we are getting to know her. Lottie is about 2 years old and has had a few litters of puppies in her previous life.

Lottie LOVES humans; she prefers to be cuddled up with her people, basking in the attention and affection. She likes the company of other dogs and has become inseparable with her doggie foster brother. She doesn't yet understand squeak toys, leading us to believe she didn't have them in her previous life. She loves bones and antlers, and spends hours chewing them. She'll occasionally show interest in chasing a tennis ball. She's quite green on a leash - when she encountered leash pressure initially, she would lie down and refuse to move, though this improves every day - and will need continued walking lessons in her forever home. Lottie is looking for a home with a yard. She is crate and house trained in her foster home. She has not been tested with children or cats, though her foster believes she'd do very well with children old enough to have impulse control.

Lottie is very submissive when put into new situations, or when spooked. For example, a sudden loud noise will send her running to the bedroom to hide on the closet, and she won't be coaxed out, and she may submissive pee. As she gets more comfortable in the home, and her humans refrain from coddling her and instead teach her how to be brave, she improves and gains confidence. But it's important to note that she'll require patience and time to overcome this quirk.

A note from foster mom: Lottie is a cuddle bug who wants to simply love her human. She smiles and wiggles her butt when happy so maybe her name should have been Ms Wigglebutt. She gets along well other dogs but wants human interaction. She will need a few days to feel confident and comfortable in her new home so don't rush it. She's a little skinny right now but we are working on it and expect that she will fill out in her furever home. She will need leash training as she doesn't really like it. She will walk on a loose leash once she feels comfortable with her human. She sleeps through the night and is house broken in her foster home. Lottie spills her food out of her food dish, something she came into foster doing. Lottie will make someone very happy as she's a gem.

If you are interested in adopting, please complete an adoption application. Because we are still understaffed due to COVID19, we will only be able to email those applicants that are approved to schedule a meet and greet. Thank you in advance for your understanding if you don't hear back from us regarding your application.

animal.description:
About Mina (notes from her foster family):

Mina is a shy and gentle girl who has an ocean of sweetness just waiting to pour out to you - if you only show her a little kindness and patience. She was brought to the shelter with an older male dog, and in foster with us, she opened up to our dog first before learning from him that we are trustworthy humans. Now, she plays with our dog daily, so I'd highly recommend her as a second dog! After two weeks with her, we know that she...
... is crate trained, potty trained, walks like a dream on leash, is fine to stay home alone if you leave the TV on (ie. some human voices)
... does not know how to play with dog toys, chew bully sticks, sleep in a dog bed, walk up stairs
... tolerates just fine a bath, nail dremel, grooming / brushing / general handling - she's been great letting me wipe her paws after walks
... is somewhat food motivated - for bedtime routine, we toss treats in her crate and she goes in no problems
When you get to know her, Mina is such an easy going, low maintenance girl. My heart swells every time she comes over and asks for pets by pawing at me. She will definitely be a blessing to her forever family.

Please contact us for further information and visit our website to complete an adoption application:
www.twodogfarms.com/adopt

Adoption fees are $300.
She is located in Los Anegels currently.

info@twodogfarms.com

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bonnie is a sweet, happy-go-lucky girl. She loves to please people and be loved on. She was found on someone's doorstep with an infection in both her ears. Dr Scholl at Chickasaw Animal Hospital did surgery on her ears. As a result of the infections, Bonnie is deaf, but looks you in the eye for direction. This gentle dog is the sweetest animal who loves to love you! She is great with kittens, cats, puppies, and adult dogs. She lies on her beds and goes outside to potty. Bonnie would be best in a home with older/mature children since she cannot hear and little kids playing or running may startle her since she cannot not hear them coming. If given the chance, Bonnie could jump a 4 foot fence, so a 6' fence is required and owners should be obervservant of her while outside as she cannot hear you to call her back home.
